report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old female with childhood onset depression with auditory hallucinosis and staring spells.
MEDICATIONS: Lithium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This patient and the parent report that the patient’s symptoms of staring and spacing have dramatically reduced at this time.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for an individual of this age with a 9 Hz, 70 V posterior dominant rhythm and posterior slow waves of youth.  LAMBDA activity is noted when the patient looks about the room.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in background theta.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Of note, even prior to hyperventilation when the patient is looking about the room, when not stimulated, she seems to become drowsy with brief vertex waves followed by an alerting.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  70 to 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In contrast to her previous record, no temporal wicket was identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old, right-handed woman with epilepsy for the past nine years, last seizure 2002 without loss of consciousness.  Seizures are characterized by a few minutes of confusion preceded by an aura of smelling fish and hearing seagulls.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, well organized with a 10.5 to 11 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Comparison with this patient’s previous EEGs may be valuable to localize seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

HR: 	80 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to a previous EEG in 2005.No epileptiform  features were identified in either study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 18-year-old woman two months pregnant who stopped Depakote when she became pregnant.  Now with breakthrough seizures and abdominal pain.
MEDICATIONS: none?
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 50 to 60 uV alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS are identified in stage II sleep.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and does not produce changes in the background.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This EEG was compared to two previous EEGs: one in 2001 and one in 2003.  Neither of these were associated with epileptiform activity.  The first EEG in 2001 was recorded one day after the initiation of Depakote, at which time it might have been possible to see the epileptiform activity.  Careful review of this patient’s other  childhood studies may be important to provide appropriate treatment in pregnancy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 9-year-old, right-handed male with staring spells, attention deficit disorder, mild cerebral palsy, developmental delay with delayed walking at age three.  Breach delivery, anxiety, hyperactivity, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with 50 to 70 V and age-appropriate quantities of background theta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in theta with one or two shifting asymmetries but no definite lateralization.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in amplitude of the alpha rhythm with an increase in background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record and no significant lateralizing features were seen. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with tonic-clonic seizures x 2.  Past history of epilepsy but currently on no medications, schizophrenia, and cocaine abuse as well as benzodiazepine ingestion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Trazodone, Seroquel, Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8.5 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by symmetric, rhythmic theta.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving at lower and faster flash frequencies with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep or using special electrodes could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year-old woman with 2 episodes with loss of consciousness
lasting minutes with postictal confusion. Past history of pulmonary emboli, bipolar
disease, migraines, benzodiazepine withdrawal, demyelination changes on the 2004
MRI, cocaine and benzodiazepine dependence.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet, Valium, Lovenox, Famotidine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 ·
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no hyperventilation or
photic stimulation. Previous tracings are not available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hertz alpha rhythm
with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Features of drowsiness
include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta. Muscle artifact was picked
up in a T4 electrode throughout the entire study.
HR: : 60-70 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. The
beta described above may be due to this patient's benzodiazepine exposure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16-year-old male/female with ADHD, sleep apnea, violent behavior, depression, Elavil overdose with agitation and violent behavior. Previously on Tegretol.
MEDICATIONS: Haldol, Midazolam, Vecuronium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing a small amount of theta. Following hyperventilation, drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
HR:  106 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this child with an overdose and additional CNS-acting medications, there is no change on this EEG despite the adjustment.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3.1-year-old male with a history of syncope, cyanosis treated with ice.  More than one episode of loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the child is awake. In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching 100 V and some posterior slow waves of youth.  An attempt is made with hyperventilation and there is some background slowing identified with hyperventilation, although the full three minutes could not be completed.  LAMBDA was seen in portions of the record.  Very brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of background slowing.
HR:  132 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The normal developmental milestones have been achieved.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy and clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 44-year-old woman with change in mental status found confused, sleepy, and with a 10-minute loss of time. Left leg weakness and pain.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Brief drowsiness is primarily characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in background beta.
Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort.  The patient seems to be falling asleep slightly in hyperventilation. In hyperventilation, there is a brief burst of temporal 5 to 7 Hz activity, which is less than 3 seconds in duration but is slightly irregular.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Probably normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above have essentially the characteristics of a normal variant such as rhythmic and temporal theta of drowsiness.  However, this is slightly irregular.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Probably normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy since 2002 with an aura of stuttering, shortness of breath, headache, and postictal confusion, seizure-free for the past three months.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 40 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by theta activity occasionally seen in the temporal or central regions.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  During relaxed wakefulness, the patient had occasional episodes of unilateral twitching of the left arm without impairment of awareness.  This was not associated with a change in the EEG.
HR:  106 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These features are similar to this patient’s previous EEG.  The twitching was not associated with an EEG stop correlate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness is characterized by some hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing. CLINICAL CORRELATION: Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be valuable.  Previous EEGs were not available at this time.  These results are similar to this patient’s previous study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old, right-handed male with seizures for the past two years, past history of stroke with right hemiparesis for ten years, HIV for ten years, hepatitis C, and seizures two weeks ago associated with low Dilantin levels.  Typical seizures: clammy hands, sweating, shakiness with incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort and the patient seems to be drowsy during hyperventilation with slow rolling eye movements.  Additional features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm with rhythmic central theta followed by vertex waves in stage I sleep.  In brief stage II sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles were identified.
Photic stimulation elicits a brief driving response.  There appears to be LAMBDA identified with photic stimulation.  The patient also starts to drift off at the end of photic stimulation.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features are identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Correlation with this patient’s previous EEGs may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 30-year-old, right-handed female with episodes of feeling as if everything becomes dark and strange lasting several seconds followed by feeling normal.  Episodes are infrequent following MVA 8/20/02 without head injury.  These symptoms occur less than one time per month.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Sleep deprived digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 Hz, 60 V posterior dominant rhythm in what appears to be posterior slow waves of youth.  The patient becomes quite drowsy and in drowsiness there are hypersynchronous bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude frontal theta and delta.  On one or two occasions, this appears to be a notch, but there is no definitive spike and slow wave activity.  Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces bursts of rhythmic, relatively symmetric high amplitude mixed theta and delta activity.  On one or two occasions this is notched, but again there is no definitive epileptiform activity.  Immediately following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is a single right temporal sharp wave.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive epileptiform features were identified in this record.  While there is some notched, rhythmic, frontal slowing, there is no definitive spike and slow wave activity.  In addition, with a single right temporal sharp wave, this must be considered artifactual rather than necessarily indicative of epileptiform activity.  To further characterize this patient’s symptoms, a follow-up study or more prolonged study may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old female with epilepsy for the past three years who presents with left facial twitching and a burning feeling on the left side of the body.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Norvasc, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the or at the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient has a transition in and out of drowsiness on multiple occasions. Features in that transition include bursts of rhythmic, frontally predominant delta activity, as well as an increase in background beta with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  There are brief portions of the record with features of stage II sleep, which is fragmented and not sustained.  Features include vertex waves and spindles followed by arousal.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation is associated with a photoelectric effect, but no clear driving. Temporal wicket in the transition in and out of sleep from the left is seen.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If further characterization of this patient’s epilepsy is important, a more prolonged study capturing her spells may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 34-year-old woman with seizures since 1999, complex partial in type.  Her last seizure was two years ago in 2001.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standing 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was performed for only less than one minute because the patient felt uncomfortable. Photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized.  There is a 9 to 10 Hz, 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. The alpha rhythm was well attenuated with eye opening. MU rhythm was identified in the central area.  Hyperventilation was performed for less than one minute.  Post-hyperventilation the patient became drowsy with slow rolling eye movements and with attenuation of the background.  In drowsiness, posterior slowing of 4 to 5 Hz activity is seen.  The posterior occipital slowing has harmonic features with the alpha activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.  The occipital slowing during drowsiness is an unusual pattern and a repeat EEG may be helpful in distinguishing between the occipital harmonic features versus a pathological pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 37-year-old right-handed female with epilepsy since
2001, average 2 to 3 seizures per month. Prior to her EEG test, the
patient was noted by the tech to have lip smacking,repetitive hand
movements and confusion which lasted less than 5 minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Carbatrol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG performed in the lab using standard
10-20 system of electrode placement and one lead channel of EKG. EEG
was performed with hyperventilation and photic stimulation. The EEG
was performed from wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG looks
symmetric with beta activity in the frontal region and an alpha rhythm
of 8.5 to 9 Hz with 20 to 30 mV. Sleeping stages were not accomplished
in this record. In hyperventilation, there is increased amplitude
bilaterally with slowness in the frontocentral area that returns to
baseline in less than 30 seconds. Photic stimulation activates mild
driving bilaterally.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal findings or epileptiform features were
observed on this study. Based on the patient's history long-term
monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old left-handed woman with epilepsy since age 7; last seizure in December.  Also with hyperlipidemia, hypertension, psychological difficulties, and a history of abuse.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, antihypertensives, Paxil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with rhythmic central theta activity. Hyperventilation was performed with good effort producing an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep or recording one of the patient’s events could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 7; last seizure in 2002.  Previous EEGs normal.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 to 60 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by a prominent increase in background beta.  This is followed by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with some rhythmic central theta.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a prominent increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old woman with a history of MI December 1995,  CABG x 5, stent x 4, hypertension, and angina for right CEA.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin and antihypertensives.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized. There is a 9 to 10 Hz, 30 to 40 V posterior dominant rhythm, with a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.  Sleep was not achieved in this record.  Occasional bilateral theta activity is seen in early drowsiness.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal features or epileptiform discharges were seen in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old woman admitted for right CEA.
MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives.  Heparin was given at 9:30 AM.
INTRODUCTION: Portable digital video EEG is performed in the OR using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The recording begins at 8:20 AM and concludes at 10:40 AM.  Incision was made at 9:07 AM.  The clamp was placed at 9:36 AM and unclamped at 10:21 and 10:23 AM.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized. After the patient is sedated and then given anesthetics, bilateral attenuation of the background with increased theta and beta activity were identified.  Significant muscle movement artifact was reduced after anesthetics were given.  The carotid was clamped at 9:36:27 without significant change in the EEG.  However, some muscle artifact is seen on the left.  The carotid was unclamped at 10:21 and 10:23 AM.  Doppler was performed at 10:37 to confirm patency and the EEG ended at 10:40.  Throughout the monitoring, no significant changes were seen on the EEG.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No significant EEG changes were identified during the operation.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with epilepsy, alcohol withdrawal, seizures, hypertension, CHF, and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, insulin, Oxcarbazepine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha with an increase in background beta followed by theta.  The patient is noted to be confused when she is maximally alert as well as when she is drowsy.
Photic stimulation did not elicit a clear driving response.
HR:  68 BPM with occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Despite the normal EEG, the patient was determined to be confused by the technologist during the study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 13-year-old male with a history of headaches preceded by a buzzing noise, nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia.  Headaches are associated with falling, black outs, staring, and unresponsiveness.
MEDICATIONS: Aleve.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG shows an alpha rhythm of 11 Hz, 30 V.  Alpha squeak is also seen at eye closure. Low voltage frontocentral beta and a bit of theta are also seen in wakefulness.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.  Symmetric Theta waves are seen during hyperventilation.  As the patient becomes drowsy, central theta and delta waves are identified.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Normal EEG does not exclude the possibility of epilepsy.  A repeat EEG may be helpful to identify focal or epileptiform features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 8.8-year-old female with an episode of nocturnal seizure, generalized tonic-clonic movements, and foaming of the mouth during sleep.  The patient was born 32 weeks early and has asthma.
MEDICATIONS:  Flovent and Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is fairly organized and symmetric.  There is a 9 Hz, 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of frontocentral beta activity. A MU rhythm at 8.3 Hz was identified.   Hyperventilation elicited rhythmic slowing.   Drowsiness produced hypnagogic hypersynchrony of slow theta activity.  In sleep, a few spindles were seen, maximum in the central vertex area.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform discharges were seen in this EEG tracing.  However, normal EEG does not exclude the possibility of epilepsy or a seizure disorder.   If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG with prolonged sleeping or sleep deprivation may be recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old woman with a history of seizure disorder starting at age two. Her last seizure was in April 2001 when she stopped her medication due to a pregnancy. Her seizures types are absence or generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II to III sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric and well organized.  There is a 10 Hz, 100 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of frontocentral beta activity.  During hyperventilation, two isolated bursts of generalized slowing were identified.  In drowsiness, there are multiple vertex sharp waves and a two small spikes were identified in the left temporal region.  Photic stimulation elicited symmetric driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison with previous EEGs this EEG tracing did not show 3 Hz spike wave nor poly spike slow wave discharge.  This tracing may be suggestive of maturation of the central nervous system are possibly that the patient has outgrown her seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old woman with epilepsy
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  In stage I sleep, vertex waves and POSTS are seen.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces a small degree of background slowing but no spike and slow wave activity.  Photic stimulation produces a small degree of driving. The patient starts to fall asleep during photic.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to previous EEGs, no generalized spike and slow wave activity was seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 32-year-old woman with a history of generalized spike and slow wave activity who ran out of Topiramate for several days and had a tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, oral contraceptives.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is high amplitude, well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 75 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing a handful of bursts of paroxysmal theta, but no spike and slow wave activity.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep, as well as abundant POSTS.  There are no definite spike and slow wave discharges seen in stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed following sleep and does not clearly activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  For this individual, recent EEGs have not identified generalized spike and slow wave or poly spike and slow wave activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 64-year-old woman with coronary artery disease, mitral valve insufficiency, and carotid stenosis.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy nor cerebrovascular disease.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old male status-post OHT in 2000 with viral CMP, episodes of feeling strange, cloudy, weird, and disillusioned. – check spelling in this section
MEDICATIONS: CellCept, Cozaar, aspirin, Cardizem, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10.5 Hz, 60 V posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is some artifact in the background, but none substantially compromises the record.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in rhythmic background theta.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Towards the close of the record, the patient is described as “antsy” and at this time, there is rhythmic, hypersynchronous theta activity compatible with a drowsy state with occasional vertex waves and then brief arousals.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is an important consideration or if there are concerns about other transient physiologic changes, a follow-up study in the lab could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through brief sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old woman with headaches, vertigo, blurry vision, and occasionally falling.  Symptoms present for the last year with paroxysmal episodes, the last one two days ago. Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: Inderal, Prozac, Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a modest amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and does not significantly activate the record.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background generalized beta with slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving bilaterally.
HR:  __ BPM. Check prelim sheet
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing one of these patient’s spells or additional sleep recording could be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old woman with syncopal spells associated with headaches occurring twice a week of unknown length of time.  Patient has episodes of feeling dizzy, hypertension, asthma, emphysema, depression, anxiety, and chest pain.
MEDICATIONS: Prozac, Diltiazem, Klonopin, and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is a one-hour EEG.  The patient experienced some of her symptoms during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake, alert, and interactive.  She is observed to have tremulousness of the arms and face in wakefulness without EEG change.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record with poor effort.  This increases the patient’s trembling including facial twitching and the patient is slow to respond, however, the EEG throughout the entire hyperventilation is normal.  During this one-hour EEG, the patient again experiences the arm and face trembling at 11:02.  The tech again performs testing. The patient initially has difficulty responding, but then answers questions appropriately.  The EEG remains normal with a normal awake pattern.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal one-hour video EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  No cardiac dysrhythmia was identified.  Consideration for a non-neurologic cause for this patient’s symptoms is appropriate at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal one-hour video EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old male from Pennsylvania Nursing Home.  Past medical history of Parkinson’s disease, Alzheimer’s disease, hypercholesterolemia, alcohol abuse, asthma, hepatitis, cirrhosis, hypertension, anxiety, depression, and dementia.
MEDICATIONS: Aricept, aspirin, and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and low voltage.  There is an 8 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and excessively diffuse beta activity.  The patient easily fell to sleep and frequent REM sleep was recorded.  The patient would wake up from REM sleep and then fall back to sleep.  POSTS activity was recognized in light sleep, and rhythmic slowing was seen in drowsiness.  Stage ___ Sleep was evidenced by a mixed frequency-----, and REM sleep was evidenced by rapid oscillatory eye movements with a low voltage background.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. POSTS activity is a normal variant.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.  REM in a routine EEG may be due to sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disorder.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old female with epilepsy. No other information is available.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The technologist has difficulty communicating with the patient and therefore it is difficult to assess maximal wakefulness.  In maximum wakefulness, the EEG appears to be reasonably well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background beta activity.  There may be an area of very subtle accentuation of beta in the right centrotemporal region.  Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.  POSTS are noted in stage I sleep as well.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  42 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Clinical evaluation may be helpful regarding the sinus bradycardia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old female with longstanding epilepsy with recent breakthrough seizures and compliance challenges.
MEDICATIONS: Doxepin, Effexor, Phenobarbital, and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a primarily asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes sleep, but in wakefulness there is an 8.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  In sleep, there are abundant vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and POSTS.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  50 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Either a repeat tracing using special electrodes or with sleep deprivation may be helpful. Alternatively, correlation with previous EEGs may be valuable. These results are similar to previous studies.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old woman with epilepsy 17 to 18 years ago with multiple normal EEGs in the past.  This is this patient’s third EEG.  She reports back and neck pain followed by loss of consciousness with some shaking and clenching of her teeth.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Effexor, _________.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.   Drowsiness is characterized by increased background beta activity. There is a lot of artifact at the T1/T2 electrodes.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record, but the patient seems very sad and/or fearful during hyperventilation.  Photic stimulation is completely obscured by photoelectric artifact.
HR:  40 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Due to the technical problems described above, this study should be repeated.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy for 18 years, three normal EEGs, including one three months ago.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Effexor, Actonel.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  The patient had her symptoms of teeth grinding during this EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  In hyperventilation, there is rhythmic slowing bilaterally.  She grinds her teeth during hyperventilation with occasional snoring.  No epileptiform features were associated with this, and the patient continued to have an awake pattern.  She remains responsive with a translator during these symptoms, but seems to be having some respiratory difficulty.  Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, and POSTS.   Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  52 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is this patient’s fourth normal EEG.  Her symptoms during hyperventilation do not appear to be seizures.  ENT evaluation may be warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old woman with progressive memory loss over the past three months.  Past history of MVA as well as a basilar artery aneurysm, which was coiled two years ago.  History of alcohol abuse and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  There is an intermittent asymmetry seen in the alpha rhythm, and on some occasions the alpha rhythm is higher on the left than the right, ranging from 15 to 30 V.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and does not substantially effect the record.    Drowsiness follows and is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with symmetric background theta.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If this patient’s memory problems are intermittent and paroxysmal, additional EEG monitoring could be of use. If epilepsy is a strong consideration, a repeat study capturing sleep could also be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 38-year-old woman with recurrent seizures, history of head trauma at age 21, ran out of medications and abused cocaine with subsequent seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Dilantin, insulin, Erythromycin, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  The patient is described as exceptionally drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm.  Much of the drowsy record is characterized by slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm with an increase in both beta and theta.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  There are rare, shifting asymmetries.  The patient is intermittently alerted from stage II sleep, but subsequently drifts back to sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed with attempts to alert the patient.  There is minimal driving at faster flash frequencies and then the patient drifts back to sleep.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG primarily in sleep within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no definite focal or epileptiform features seen in this record.  Additional clinical evaluation may be helpful regarding this patient’s hypersomnolence.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG primarily in sleep within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 21-year-old woman with obesity and syncope associated with a severe headache, dizziness, and then loss of consciousness. History of asthma and seizures in childhood with family history of febrile seizures.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by a small increase in theta as well as anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits driving at 3 Hz and faster flash frequencies, but there was no spike and slow wave activity associated with the driving response.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were seen in this record.  A normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy and if seizures are an important consideration, a repeat study could be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 47-year-old woman with multiple MRIs in the past compatible with multiple sclerosis, intermittent spasticity and clonus on the left, and possible seizures.  Acute hepatitis of unclear etiology.
MEDICATIONS: Compazine, Ativan, thiamine, and Zyprexa.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient was medicated with Ativan prior to the test. The patient has modest, involuntary movements.  She has none of her severe spasms.  Stimulation of the patient in an attempt to elicit the spasms is not performed.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is rich in beta frequency activity.  In maximal weakness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz, with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As she becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background beta activity with occasional vertex waves.  The overall background is low voltage.
Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response at 3 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  112 BPM, with rare PVCs.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The generous beta may be due to this patient’s medications.  In that this patient’s left-sided motor activity had been thought to be epileptiform in nature, if desired, a repeat EEG with stimulation of the patient to elicit the motor would be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 45-year-old woman with a history of migraines and meningitis.  The patient has a disorder of neck twitching.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed. This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is a prominent dominant rhythm of 11 Hz. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  In drowsiness, rhythmic central theta activity is seen.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Hyperventilation increases the amplitude in the background.  Photic stimulation elicits mild driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform activity is identified in this recording. Neck twitching was not observed during this recording. If seizure activity is clinically indicated, a repeat EEG is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with meningitis and migraine headaches with the appearance of epilepsy following the meningitis.  Tremors, and gait dysfunction.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in background beta.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation is reviewed with the digital video EEG.  The technologist reports that the patient is getting antsy and agitated during photic stimulation, although the audio is off.  A bilateral brief driving response is seen and there is also some head-rocking artifact.  The technologist’s notes are excellent, although there is no audio.  The patient is telling the tech that the photic stimulation is making her shake.  Reviewing the EEG, there is head-rocking artifact in the background and the tech describes the patient as having a panic attack, but there is no epileptiform activity and the patient does permit the conclusion of photic stimulation, which elicits a bilateral driving response.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Of note, the patient is tachycardic at baseline and becomes panicked during photic stimulation.  Evaluation as to the cause of these symptoms may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Simply a low voltage pattern is not an abnormality for a subject of this age.  Pathological drowsiness could produce the pattern seen above with limited sustained wakefulness and a rapid transition into a theta/drowsy pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old female athlete with recurrent episodes where she feels as if she has visual black outs with one pre-syncopal spell and a positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet/Vicodin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth are identified.  At baseline, the patient’s heart rate is 56 to 66 BPM.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in the amplitude as well as a small degree of rhythmic theta.  Briefly during hyperventilation, the heart rate increases to 100 BPM. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic central theta with an intermittent anterior spread of the alpha and some hypersynchronous mixed alpha and theta frequency activity.  There are rare vertex waves and K complexes.
Photic stimulation produces symmetric bilateral driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  As described above.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If appropriate, a follow-up study with additional maneuvers may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage II sleep.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with hypertension, obstructive sleep apnea, and seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, there is rhythmic, 5 Hz, sharply contoured activity with a flat-top shape in the left temporal region.  This may appear in bursts lasting up to 1.5 seconds.  There is a very slight degree of variability in the activity.  Identical, 5.2 Hz activity is identified from the right in similar states.  This is also seen at the close of hyperventilation as the patient becomes drowsy.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The findings described above are most compatible with a psychomotor variant.  They have the characteristic 5 Hz activity.  On the left, there is just a touch of variability in terms of actual frequency, but the identical activity is seen on the right in the same sleep state.  To further define this, a repeat study in deeper stages of sleep could be of use, however, a previous study in stage II sleep earlier this year did not identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Portable digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.

report:
History:	80 year old woman with a history of seizures.  No reported seizures since ~ 2008.
She now reports left sided head pain.
Medications:	Tegretol, Celebrex
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5-10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,

report:

MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives, Advil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage with generous background beta activity and a low voltage, 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Frequent eye blinking is noted throughout wakefulness. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving
HR:  80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The generous background beta can be seen in the setting of anxiety or medication effect.  A low voltage pattern is not abnormal in this age group.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 30-year-old male with epilepsy since infancy with tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Portions of the awake record demonstrate a vigorous, 10 Hz, 10 V MU rhythm from the left central region, which is rarely seen on the right.  There is some rocking artifact but no definite epileptiform activity seen in the background.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small amount of background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits a photoelectric effect.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The presence of unilateral MU is not pathologic
There is a brief epoch of EEG December 16 for this patient, which identifies a normal awake pattern with again the unilateral MU identified from the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old, right-handed male with a history of convulsive generalized tonic-clonic seizures since age five.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record in a patient who seems to be very sleepy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by intermittent, rhythmic generalized theta, as well as some slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drowsy and elicits a driving response.  Hyperventilation did not elicit a change in the background.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old woman with hypertension, diabetes, thyroid disease, and epilepsy. Positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 21-year-old male with a history of seizures x 2 during and after cardiac catheterization in 2001.  Patient received heart surgery in 1992.  Patient had one seizure during a cardiac procedure while receiving nitroglycerine injection.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Lipitor, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and well organized. There is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation mildly increased the slow activity of theta and delta waves in the frontocentral area.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient became drowsy, which is evidenced by a mixed frequency of brain activity. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving, as well as a photoelectric artifact.
HR:  54 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
History:	31 year old man with a history of seizures, now presents with left  sided weakness
and facial droop.
Medications:	Depakote
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11-11.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart
rate <60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A single EKG lead demonstrates
heart rate <60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A single EKG lead demonstrates
heart rate <60 bpm

report:
History:	32 year old man who presents with events concerning for seizures.
Medications:	DILANTIN,  DEPAKOTE ER
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for ~25 hours from 11/3/2015 till 11/4/2015.   Nursing-
initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.  Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed
at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All
automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse, frontally predominant 5-10uV, 18-25Hz activity is also seen.
During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more
prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the
record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Summary of Findings:
No electrographic seizures
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a normal ~25-hour continuous video EEG. No clinical or electrographic seizures are present.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a normal ~25-hour continuous video EEG. No clinical or electrographic seizures are present

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16-year-old girl with new onset seizures in November 2003, and one seizure in December 2003.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and well organized for a subject of this age.  There is a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient falls into light sleep, which is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and POSTS.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake and asleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Migraine headache.  Patient requires clearance for driver's license.
This is a 26-year-old woman with epilepsy at age 9, seizure-free since November 2013.  Patient experiences rusty taste in her mouth followed by exhaustion.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A 24-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with impedances under 5 kilohms.  Some head rocking artifact was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm.  Prominent temporal wicket was noted.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements with rhythmic central theta.  POSTS were noted in stage 1 sleep.
At the close of the record, the patient transitions to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and produces a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th EEG for this patient.  Previous studies were performed February 6, 2004, March 28, 2005, and May 7, 2013.  The 2013 study was normal as this study.  No epileptiform features were noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old male with slurred speech, left arm numbness, and blurry vision for two days, treated with Dilantin.  Negative CT.  History of TIA and depression.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Plavix, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes an 11 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of frontocentral beta activity.  In drowsiness, there is a prominent increase in background theta with occasional vertex waves.   Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  POSTS are identified in stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and elicits a brief driving response at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There was occasional snore artifact identified, and this patient was falling asleep in photic stimulation suggesting that this individual may be excessively tired.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed woman, with history of possible schizophrenia and/or hypertension with episodes of syncope since the age of 13, as well as episodic confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Elavil, Seroquel, Depakote, ASA, Amitriptyline, Pravastatin, Ranitidine
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm. The patient is quite drowsy, transitioning from wakefulness into drowsiness and then as she starts to transition into stage 2 sleep there is spontaneous arousal. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude and a small amount of slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 78bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features identified. The transitions in and out of sleep with bursts of sleep occur even during photic stimulation may occur in the context of sleep deprivation. It may also be seen in an individual who is sleepy or any other cause.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 15-year-old female with syncope versus seizures, headaches, dizziness, with loss of consciousness.

MEDICATIONS: Adderall.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a sleep deprived study.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and rare LAMBDA.  Photic stimulation is performed early on in the record.  There is brief driving as well as a photoelectric effect.  Following this, the patient becomes drowsy with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is seen primarily late in the recording with an increase in rhythmic background theta. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.

Hyperventilation produces a small amount of background slowing.

HR:  72 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up tracing with deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old woman with epilepsy for the past two years after head trauma.  The seizures begin with hand shaking and loss of consciousness, convulsive activity followed by postictal confusion.  Seizures triggered by a fall in the shower.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well-organized background with a 10 Hz symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is temporal wicket activity identified.  The wicket activity on the left is slightly higher amplitude and it is slightly irritative in its nature, but there is no definite spike or slow wave activity.  As the patient reaches deeper stages of sleep, there are vertex waves and POSTS, but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained and the patient intermittently arouses from sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy and does not activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no definite epileptiform activity, although there is some suspicious activity underlying what is likely a normal variant.  To clarify this, a repeat study with more prolonged sleep would be helpful to determine if in fact there is underlying left temporal sharp activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old woman with post-traumatic epilepsy for the past two years.  Last seizure occurred four months ago.  Seizures begin with focal motor with secondary generalization.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well organized 11 Hz, 15 to 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are intermittent wicket spikes identified more from the left than the right temporal regions, which disappear in stage II sleep.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.  There is also the occurrence of benign sleep transience in this patient, as well as vertex sharp waves.
Photic stimulation activates the record at higher flash frequencies to some degree.
HR:  74 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The wicket spike activity disappears in stage II sleep, which signifies a benign variant of EEG changes. A sleep deprived EEG would be useful in order to identify latent epileptiform activity in the temporal areas.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta activity.  Slow rolling eye movements are noted, with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles in stage II sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving at faster flash frequencies.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
