report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old male with epilepsy with seizures since 2008.

MEDICATIONS:  Magnesium Oxide, ASA, Metoprolol, Enalapril, HCTZ, Keppra

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR:    78 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the second normal EEG for this adult.  If further characterization of his epilepsy is important, a follow up study capturing more extended sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
History:	25 year old woman with a history of nocturnal seizures.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is seen  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Beta, excessive
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 46-year-old woman, right handed woman, with diabetes, who presented to the emergency room with gastroenteritis and lightheadedness, and then went on to have right arm twitching.  Sometimes the patient experienced right arm numbness, head rocking, and right arm shaking.

MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, pravastatin, metformin, others.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This was an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm.  The patient transitions in and out of an awake and drowsy state, 14 and 6, 14, and 6 was noted symmetrically in the frontal regions on rare occasions in that transition.

The technologist performed testing for the patient to make sure that the patient was able to be awake and alert.  With cognitive testing, a normal awake EEG pattern was noted.

The patient has an episode of hand tremulousness.  The patient remains awake, alert, conversant with the technologist.  In addition, the EEG pattern during this twitch demonstrates a well organized, well defined normal awake pattern.

Very brief epochs of stage II sleep were recorded.  The patient was not observed to have any involuntary movements in sleep.

At 1:40 p.m. the patient had an episode of head rocking from side to side.  This was not associated with a change in the EEG, although it did produce some tremulousness.

Heart rate:  90 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake through brief stage II sleep



CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The patient demonstrated 2 motor behaviors during the EEG.  The first was tremulousness of the hand, the second was head rocking from side to side.  Neither of these carried an EEG signature.  Correlation with this patient's clinical picture and imaging is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake through brief stage II sleep

report:
.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old with cerebral palsy, episodes of body jerking, and spasticity.

MEDICATIONS: NONE

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This EEG was recorded for a patient sitting up in a wheelchair.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well-organized with a 10 Hz, symmetric, alpha rhythm.  The patient starts to drift off to sleep, losing head control.  He is unable to get comfortable in the wheelchair.

Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record not activating the record.  The patient drifts attempts to drift off to sleep with drop out of alpha, central theta and then brief central beta, but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained given the mobility issues.

Photic stimulation did not activate the record.  Heart rate 126 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If additional information is needed, alternative EEG recording strategies may be necessary.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed male with history of aortic aneurysm, hypertension, asthma, going to the OR for aortic root replacement.

MEDICATIONS:  Midazolam, Fentanyl, Propofol, Isoflurane, Ceftriaxone, Vancomycin, Solu Medrol, Lidocaine, Potassium, Norepinephrine

REASON FOR STUDY:  Aortic arch bypass surgery.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes during aortic bypass surgery.  The patient was recorded during the entire procedure.  The technician was present during the entire procedure and the physician was present during the critical parts of the procedure.  Feedback was given to the surgeon about changes in the EEG.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  During the procedure the right side of the head is cooled more than the left which may effect the reading of the EEG as was noted during this case.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a baseline posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  Normal frontal central beta seen.  As the procedure goes on, the incision occurs at 9:16 in the morning, heparin is given at 9:31, bypass of the head and body is done at 9:51, aorta clamped at 9:54, cooling starts at 9:56.  During all this time the EEG is at baseline, however, around 9:56 when the cooling begins, there started to be noted some slowing, specifically around 10:01 a.m. in the morning there is an asymmetry where the right side is slightly slower than the left with some sharply contoured activity in the temporal region, that at times becomes periodic and is not clearly seen with a lower amplitude.  This pattern continues as the left hemisphere also starts to become slow, but remains asymmetric up to the time where the EEG starts becomes completely suppressed which occurs first on the right hemisphere, but completely on the entire brain at around 10:13.  At this time there is some burst suppression and by 10:25 it is in complete suppression.  There is cardiac arrest at 10:30 a.m. and he starts to be rewarmed at 10:47 a.m.  He is removed from head bypass at 10:08 a.m. and noticeable bursts of activity start to be seen at around 11:04.  The EEG returns to baseline by 11:21:36 and there is no longer an asymmetry over the right hemisphere.

All the changes that were discussed above were discussed and described to the surgeon.

IMPRESSION:  This is an EEG recording during aortic root replacement surgery with a mild asymmetry noted while cooling, thought to be related to cooling artifact of the right side of the head predominating compared to the left, which after surgery and burst suppression was achieved appeared to return to baseline.  A normal EEG at baseline was seen at the end of the surgery.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is an uneventful aortic root replacement surgery EEG recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an EEG recording during aortic root replacement surgery with a mild asymmetry noted while cooling, thought to be related to cooling artifact of the right side of the head predominating compared to the left, which after surgery and burst suppression was achieved appeared to return to baseline.  A normal EEG at baseline was seen at the end of the surgery.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 77-year-old woman, baseline study for aortic arch surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient does not recall.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is generous beta.  The patient seems to be very anxious during the EEG and is at times inattentive.  Some sections of the record demonstrate excess theta in apparent wakefulness.  Vertex waves were noted in stage 1 sleep.  In later sections of the record, in wakefulness, the patient was moving about and the EEG was somewhat obscured by artifact.
Photic stimulation did elicit a bilateral driving response.
Heart rate 55 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is upper limits of normal for an adult of this age due to:
Background theta.
There is a little bit of shifting slowing and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No significant focal features were identified.  This study will be used for this patient's operative baseline.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is upper limits of normal for an adult of this age due to Background theta. There is a little bit of shifting slowing and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old male with an episode of generalized shaking and loss of consciousness. Sitting in his chair he fell backwards, eyes rolled up and he shook for 5 minutes.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 12 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by abundant vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles and POSTS.

Heart rate 78 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in a very sleepy patient.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  Sleep deprivation and medications may play a role in the hypersomnolent record recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in a very sleepy patient.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  26 year old left handed woman with menstrual epilepsy, nocturnal convulsions during the first weeks of her menstrual cycle.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was attempted in lab standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient has great difficulty cooperating with the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is lacking any of the normal morphologies for an adult of this age.  There is the suggestion of some sharp activity at P4; however, there are so many electrode problems that the EEG is of limited value.  Even the EKG lead did not stay on.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is quite technically limited but is remarkable for paucity of normal wave forms.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A repeat study, allowing the individual to fall asleep as well as wrapping the head to secure the quality of the electrodes is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is quite technically limited but is remarkable for paucity of normal wave forms.

report:
History: Medications: Sedation: EEG Type: Technique:


37 year old man with seizures since 2005
keppra, dilantin, flexeril, prilosec, albuterol, restoril, zoloft None
Routine, awake & drowsy
International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1fT2 electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic




Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.

No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at intermediate flash rates.

Summary of Findings:
Alpha rhythm, normal

Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old right handed woman with history of epilepsy since the age of 16, who now presents with 2 generalized tonic clonic seizures.  Of note, the patient ran out of Klonopin about a week ago and she did not take her Keppra and Zonisamide.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Lovenox, Keppra, Klonopin, Zoloft, Haldol, Terazosin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and regulated 9-10 Hz that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Excess beta is present throughout the recording.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates voltages decreased, diffuse beta appears.  Wickets are present as well during drowsy and awake.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  There is no focal slowing. Hyperventilation produces mild diffuse slowing. Photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  Excess beta could be due to medications, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, but stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical suspicion for seizures persist, a repeat study with sleep, stage II, may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not exclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  Excess beta could be due to medications, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old right handed woman with seizures since age 16, now refractory to medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Valproic Acid, Lovenox, Depakote, Keppra, Klonopin, Zoloft, Haldol, Terazosin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software as well as nurses' notes and patient's alarms were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage 1, stage 2 and deeper stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  The patient had 2 events in this recording similar to the ones in the previous day.  The first one occurred at 8:10:43 p.m. and the second one occurred at 11:47 p.m.  Both of them, the body had irregular shaking for minutes with no response to verbal or motor commands.  The patient had no EEG correlate during this time despite being unconscious.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with 2 episodes of nonepileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The 2 episodes described above had no EEG correlate, as such it is consistent with nonepileptic seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with 2 episodes of nonepileptic events.

report:
DATE OF STUDY:  October 3, 2014 through October 5, 2014.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old woman with a 2-year history of convulsions.  Eyes roll around, foaming at the mouth.  History of hypertension, epilepsy, and anxiety.
MEDICATIONS:  Xanax.  ?None versus transient.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This report includes 48 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  There were daily practice pushbuttons.  Seizure and spike detection software was utilized.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  October 3rd to October 4th:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-developed alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In drowsiness, wicket activity as well as prominent, 5 hertz rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness was noted.
Sleep was characterized by abundant beta activity and spindles.  Sleep was relatively fragmented and snoring was noted.
Seizures:  None.
Epileptiform Activity:  None.
Practice push buttons: 11:59 and 8 p.m.  No epileptiform features noted at this time.
EEG monitoring during this section of the record did not identify epileptiform activity.
October 4th to October 5th:  During this section of the record, the patient had 1 clinical event at 11 p.m. on the night of the 4th.
Background:  In sleep, there is abundant beta activity.  No transition in and out of sleep, rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness was noted.  The awake record is well organized with symmetric reactive alpha rhythm.
Interictal epileptiform abnormalities:  None.
Epileptiform seizures:  None.
Event:  11p.m., the patient had been asleep.  She seems to be somewhat drowsy.  Prior to the event, significant noise can be appreciated in the hallway, which has made it difficult to sleep.  By 10:46, there is eye opening noted.  The event is at 11 p.m.  The patient is noted to be breathing heavily, somewhat restless.  The patient pushes the button.  The nurses enter the room.  The patient is breathing heavily.  She is not conversing with the nurses, but she is following commands.  Altered and somewhat peculiar behavior is noted and at 11:02, the patient is crying and moaning.  The patient is consoled by the nurses.  At 11:04, she is responding appropriately to the nurses, but she looks away from them.  The physician enters at 11:06.  Somewhat unusual behavior persists, although there is a great deal of movement artifact, which obscures the EKG.  The overall EEG demonstrates an awake pattern.  At 11:23, she remains tearful with a normal heart rate of 78 beats per minute.
Subsequently, the patient received a tablet of Xanax and transitions back to sleep.
Heart rate 74 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG report includes the patient's final 2 days of continuous EEG monitoring.  It is remarkable for:
Two prominent normal, but epileptiform-appearing variants, rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness in wicket.
A single spell with unusual behavior, hyperventilation, and cry, but with preserved awareness and without an EEG signature.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this section of the recording.  If the behavior in question is typical of this patient's usual seizures, this session may have answered the clinical questions.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG report includes the patient's final 2 days of continuous EEG monitoring.  It is remarkable for Two prominent normal, but epileptiform-appearing variants, rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness in wicket. A single spell with unusual behavior, hyperventilation, and cry, but with preserved awareness and without an EEG signature.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 42-year-old woman with new onset seizures.  Patient awakens with tongue biting, jerking, arm stiffness and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Fifty minute digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 70 mV posterior dominant rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth were identified.
This was a sleep deprived EEG and the patient rapidly transitioned in and of stage II sleep.  She was awakened for hyperventilation, which produced an increase in amplitude of the background and then drifted immediately back into stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and posts.
Photic stimulation was performed at the end of the record.  The patient was having trouble staying awake and was drifting in and out of stage II sleep, but there was a subtle driving response seen on one occasion.
Heart rate 72 beats per minute to 108 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were seen in today's EEG. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  Of note, the patient had an episode of tachycardia develop while asleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 43-year-old female with episodes of blacking out for 2 years and 1 episode 21 years ago, now with headaches in the frontal region.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Hypertension and asthma.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydrochlorothiazide, albuterol, Cymbalta, losartan.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included  hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Continuous T4 electrode artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old woman with daily episodes for the past 2 years characterized by freezing, head jerking back and forth mostly to the left, difficulty breathing, gasping respirations.  Events last 10 seconds to 2 minutes and sometimes occur in clusters.  Diagnosis of multiple sclerosis in 2000.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not possible but photic stimulation was completed.  This was a 26 minute EEG which was primarily in wakefulness.  The patient had 6 clinical events during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG was well organized with a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  A total of 6 behavioral events were noted including 1 at the start of the EEG.  The patient rocks her head from side to side.  On one occasion she gasps and on another occasion, she put her hands to her throat.
All events were characterized by head rocking artifact.  No epileptiform features were identified before, during or after the event.  Immediately after the event, the EEG demonstrated an awake pattern.  The patient demonstrated psychomotor slowing, sometimes unable to answer questions, sometimes unresponsive.  On other occasions, she followed commands but was unable to speak or demonstrated psychomotor slowing.
Photic stimulation elicited brief driving.  The patient also had one of her spells during photic stimulation.  Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is remarkable for:
Multiple behavioral events with head rocking but without an epileptiform signature.
A normal awake pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no previous EEGs available for comparison.  The video and clinical correlates as well as the normal EEG during these events with unresponsiveness are more suggestive of a non-epileptiform behavior.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is remarkable for Multiple behavioral events with head rocking but without an epileptiform signature. A normal awake pattern.

report:
DIAGNOSIS:  Classification of seizure diagnosis, epileptiform versus nonepileptiform seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with history of epilepsy since age of 11.  She states that she has 2 types of seizures.  The 1st semiology of seizure starts with an aura of ear buzzing and ear fullness and at times, she has automatism on the right hand, which was described as “searching in the air.” Some seizure episodes were followed by a secondary generalized tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient was on Topamax 25 mg twice a day and Klonopin 1 mg 3 times a day prior to admission to EMU unit.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the EMU using the standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  An automated seizure and spike detection system and a patient activated alarm system were used.  Records were reviewed daily of EEG abnormalities and clinical events.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Interictal EEG:  From 07/02/2013 to 07/03/2013; the interictal posterior dominant rhythm consisted of 9-10 Hz activity that was moderate amount of diffuse beta activity.  Stage I sleep was characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and the presence of vertex waves.  Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and a sleep and slow waves of stage III were also observed. Hyperventilation was performed at 9:20 A.M. by physician, which led to symmetric slowing of background. Photic stimulation was performed at 10:21 A.M. and was followed by no abnormal response or clinical seizures. (Heart rate was between 60-90 per minute and was regular.)
Clinical events: All her clinical events happened during wakefulness.
On 07/03/2013, the patient was sitting at the edge of the bed at 7:40 a.m., was being examined by physician, she reported feeling numbness and tingling in both her hands, she stated that this is one of her typical seizures episodes.  This lasted 2-3 minutes.  At 7:45:21, the patient said she does not feel numbness or tingling any more.  During this episode, the patient was awake and able to answer all questions correctly. The EEG showed an awake pattern with no ictal EEG correlation.
On 07/03/2013 at 6 a.m., the patient was lying in bed. The patient was drowsy.  Then, she woke up.  There was no jerking noted, the patient pushed the alarm button at 6:13 a.m.  EEG showed awake state with no epileptic changes.  The nurse came into the room and checked the blood pressure.
IMPRESSION:  The video EEG monitoring study was normal and did not show electrographic changes consistent with the clinical events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The interictal EEG does not support the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The episodes are diagnostic for psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  A simple partial seizure cannot be ruled out by this recording, although complex partial, generalized tonic clonic, and myoclonic seizures can be ruled out.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  We did not capture all the typical seizure types including the generalized tonic-clonic seizures and further long-term monitoring admissions are recommended for capturing the rest of the events.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  The video EEG monitoring study was normal and did not show electrographic changes consistent with the clinical events.

report:

Other features of drowsiness included an increase in beta.  Some rolling eye movements were observed, but deeper stages of sleep were not identified.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving. Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
DATES OF THE RECORDING:  01/29/2013 from about 8 a.m. until 01/30/2013 until about 8 a.m.  Total length of the recording approximately 24 hours.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 33-year-old woman with a history of reported seizures since March  2011 characterized by a metallic taste in her mouth followed by loss of consciousness and convulsions.
NOTE:  The patient was sleep deprived until approximately 2 a.m. on 01/30/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include Depakote 500 mg in the morning and 250 mg in the evening, clonazepam 2 mg b.i.d. as well as 2 mg p.r.n. q.12 hours.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  Seizure detection and spike detection were activated.  The EEG recording was reviewed at least once in 24 hour period.  Medical staff notes and nursing notes were reviewed.  The patient was equipped with a push button.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 9-10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Excess diffuse beta is captured.  During sleep symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, slow wave sleep, and several epochs of REM sleep are captured.  There were no clear epileptiform discharges and no clear focal slowing.  There were no push button events.  Continuous EKG artifact is captured.
FINDINGS:
No events.
Normal awake and asleep study.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal 24-hour continuous audio video EEG monitoring.  No typical events were captured.  The excess beta could be secondary to medication effects such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  Of note, the patient was sleep deprived until  approximately 2 a.m. on 01/30/2013.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal 24-hour continuous audio video EEG monitoring.  No typical events were captured.  The excess beta could be secondary to medication effects such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  Of note, the patient was sleep deprived until  approximately 2 a.m. on 01/30/2013

report:
History:	40 year old man with episodes concerning for seizures.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity.  A brief epoch of
waveforms seen during typical REM sleep is captured.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates
premature QRS complexes, QRS complexes that change appearance and occasional up to 1.5
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A brief epoch that could represent
REM sleep is captured.  REM sleep is not typically seen in a spot/ routine EEG - please correlate
with an underlying sleep disorder.  A single EKG lead demonstrates premature QRS complexes,
QRS complexes that change appearance and occasional up to 1.5 second inter-QRS pauses.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A brief epoch that could represent
REM sleep is captured.  REM sleep is not typically seen in a spot/ routine EEG - please correlate
with an underlying sleep disorder.  A single EKG lead demonstrates premature QRS complexes,
QRS complexes that change appearance and occasional up to 1.5 second inter-QRS pauses

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 35-year-old woman who first presented with seizures in 2012, seizures recurred in 2014. Seizures may begin with an aura, previously described as twitching on the right, head turning to the left, falls, becomes paralyzed on the right, with tongue biting and foaming of the mouth, followed by drowsiness and right eye twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This was an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching 70 microvolts, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Microsleeps are noted with brief dropouts of the alpha rhythm and very brief epochs of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and K complexes.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  The patient was dropping in and out of stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation
Heart rate:  72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this individual who completed previous routine and 3 days of continuous video EEG monitoring.  None of the studies have demonstrated epileptiform activity. Microsleeps were noted today, may be due to sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disturbance.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage 2 sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old woman who presents with history of new onset seizure-like activity.  Seizure is described as sudden onset of feeling bad smell or seeing colors or at times numbness and tingling in the left face and arm followed by loss of consciousness with no convulsion.  The episode usually last for a few minutes.  She also had, at times, she may experience staring spells lasting 25-30 seconds noted by her boyfriend.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal 300 mg b.i.d., vitamin D, Elavil, and Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the EMU using a standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Records were daily reviewed for EEG abnormalities and clinical events.  Sleep and wakefulness were captured.  There was an automated spike in seizure detection system in place as well as patient activated alarm system.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Interictal EEG description:  In the most alert state, there was a posterior dominant rhythm with frequency of 10-11 Hz, 30-80 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region.  There was presence of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which was distributed symmetrically.  A stage 1 sleep was characterized by the disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  The stage 2 sleep was characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles.  A slow-wave sleep and REM sleep were also captured.  No interictal epileptiform abnormalities or evidence of focally slowing were noted.  Heart rate was approximately 70 to 90 beats per minute.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  On 08/08/2013, there was 1 pushbutton event during photic stimulation noted by technician at 1:21 p.m.  Patient was sitting on the bed complaining of smelling funny lasting for 10 seconds without any change in mental status or abnormal movements.  This episode was not associated with ictal change on EEG.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal video EEG monitoring.  No interictal epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.  The patient reported a smell of something funny, lasting 10 seconds.  At 1:21 p.m., on 08/08/2013, which were not associated with ictal change on EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Please note that simple partial seizures are not always associated with changes on a scalp EEG.  The patient's habitual seizures were not captured.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat prolonged video EEG monitoring may be helpful.
__________________________
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal video EEG monitoring.  No interictal epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.  The patient reported a smell of something funny, lasting 10 seconds.  At 1:21 p.m., on 08/08/2013, which were not associated with ictal change on EEG.

report:
LENGTH OF EEG:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 45-year-old woman who presents with a large pulmonary embolism, scheduled for an embolectomy on 6/27/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, oxycodone, trazodone, and heparin.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped-photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated very low amplitude 11 to 11.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness the background voltage is increased and the amount of theta increases as well.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped-photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving with multiple flash frequencies.  Excess diffuse beta is captured.
FINDINGS:
Low voltage.
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect.  The lack of epileptiform discharges noted on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect.  The lack of epileptiform discharges noted on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include Percocet.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording is performed according to standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
LENGTH OF RECORDING:  28 minutes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10 Hz alpha that attenuates with eyes opening.  Fast alpha variant is intermittently observed.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency of 2 gradients with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, POSTS (posterior occipital sharp transients of sleep), symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes are captured.  Ventilation is produced with a fair effort and produces no significant change in the background.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a regular heart rate.
FINDINGS:
Epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 28 minute EEG.  Lack of epileptiform discharges does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 33-year-old man with a history of seizures since age 15, the last one on June 13th, who presents to EMU for evaluation of seizures and differential diagnosis.

He has a past medical history of seizures, asthma, bronchitis, depression, migraine, and drug abuse.

MEDICATIONS:  Divalproex, methadone, Advair, and albuterol.

INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the EMU using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  An automated seizure and spike detection system and patient activated alarm system were used.  Records were reviewed daily for EEG abnormalities and clinical events.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Interictal EEG from 08/12/2013 to 08/15/2013:  In the most alert state, there is a normal posterior dominant rhythm with a frequency of 9-10 Hz seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta activity.  The stage I sleep was characterized by the disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact, vertex sharp waves, and posts.  The stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  The deeper stages of sleep were characterized by increasing amounts of delta frequency activity.  REM sleep was also captured.  Heart rate was 70-80 beats per minutes and regular.

Clinical events:  On 08/13/2013 at 7:25 p.m., there is a push button event as the patient lying in bed.  The nurse is in to check while the patient's head turned to the right with jerking in right shoulder for a few seconds.  EEG showed no ictal change.  There was normal awake background.

IMPRESSION:  This is a normal video EEG monitoring study with no interictal epileptiform abnormalities.  Patient had 1 event consisting of right arm shaking for a few seconds with no change in mental status.  There were no associated ictal changes on EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This video EEG monitoring does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If all of the patient's habitual events have not been captured, a repeat video EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal video EEG monitoring study with no interictal epileptiform abnormalities.  Patient had 1 event consisting of right arm shaking for a few seconds with no change in mental status.  There were no associated ictal changes on EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  28-year-old woman with stress-related seizures, increased after recent motor vehicle accident.  Previous victim of violence, traumatic brain injury.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, gabapentin, phenytoin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient had clinical events with shaking from side to side, preceded by an aura during this EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric reactive alpha rhythm of 9 Hz.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing.  Sleep is somewhat disrupted for this adult.  Early slow wave sleep with higher amplitude 2 Hz delta was noted.  Stage 2 sleep was also obtained.
Events:  The patient had symptoms between the time of 11:59 to 12:54.  She was able to push the button, notified the nurse and described her symptoms.  She felt a vibrating sensation in her body.  She then demonstrated very rapid, thrashing side-to-side movements.
No EEG changes were noted with these behaviors aside from artifact and no postictal slowing was identified.  The patient's most prominent motor activity was at 12:55 and then afterward she was lying motionless in the bed, her head turned to the right with a normal awake EEG.
EKG:  Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:
Normal 24-hour continuous video EEG monitoring session.
One event described by the patient as her typical seizure without EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings were discussed with the patient, who was given the diagnosis of a stress-related seizure or a nonepileptic seizure.  The patient concurred with this diagnosis as well as discontinuation of phenytoin.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION Normal 24-hour continuous video EEG monitoring session. One event described by the patient as her typical seizure without EEG correlate.

report:
EEG LENGTH:  30 minutes
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 34-year-old woman with a history of seizure disorder who now presents with increasing seizure frequency.  Her last seizure occurred approximately two weeks ago.  Her medications include Dilantin, sertraline, venlafaxine and diphenhydramine.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10-1/2 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the amount of diffuse theta and frontal central beta increases.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse background slowing as well as brief bursts of moderate to high amplitude diffuse frontally predominant somewhat rhythmic theta activity.  Similar activity is observed post hyperventilation as well as during drowsiness.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  Bursts of diffuse frontally predominant moderate to high amplitude somewhat rhythmic theta activity are also observed during photic stimulation.
A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate that is at times fewer than 60 beats per minute.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
Brief bursts of moderate to high amplitude diffuse frontally predominant theta activity that occur during hyperventilation, post hyperventilation, during drowsiness and during photic stimulation.
IMPRESSION:  This is likely a normal awake and drowsy 30-minute EEG.  Bursts of moderate to high amplitude, somewhat rhythmic theta activity that occur throughout the recording, are of uncertain clinical significance but are not clearly epileptiform.  A repeat longer study with prolonged sleep would be of benefit in this patient.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is likely a normal awake and drowsy 30-minute EEG.  Bursts of moderate to high amplitude, somewhat rhythmic theta activity that occur throughout the recording, are of uncertain clinical significance but are not clearly epileptiform.  A repeat longer study with prolonged sleep would be of benefit in this patient

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old woman with an 8 year history of epilepsy.  The patient had increased seizures for the last 5 months.  Event on New Year's Day with tachycardia and inability to speak for 3 hours.
MEDICATIONS:  Toradol, Reglan, Benadryl, others
INTRODUCTION:  A 20 minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Impedances were under 5 kilo-ohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrode.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Occasional muscle twitch artifact was noted as the patient transitioned in and out of sleep.  Brief stage 2 sleep include vertex waves and spindles.
HEART RATE 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal electroencephalogram.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and, if seizures are an important consideration, a follow up study may be of use.  Consideration for inpatient or outpatient EEG may be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal electroencephalogram.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with 8-month history of recurrent episodes of deja vu, olfactory paroxysms and a bitter taste in her mouth, history of reflux, hypertension, and migraine.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra ? Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Seizure and spike detection software was utilized.  The patient was able to push the monitor and recorded 12 events with olfactory symptoms and a bitter taste in her mouth, but none with impairment of awareness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG was well organized with symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS noted in sleep.  The patient appears to have difficulty getting to sleep and was up throughout much of the night, but brief stage II sleep was noted.
INTERICTAL EPILEPTIFORM DETECTIONS:  None.
ELECTROGRAPHIC SEIZURES:  None.
PUSH BUTTONS:  times  11:11, 11:47, 12:39, 01:50, 02:59, 04:20, 04:30, 05:02, 06:13, 08:18, 11:13 p.m.  Although one of these included a practice  pushbutton, all others were for the patient's clinical symptoms.  All demonstrated a normal awake pattern.
HEART RATE 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This first 24 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
A normal awake and sleep pattern.
The absence of epileptiform activity.
Multiple push button events for symptoms without impairment of awareness, which did not carry an EEG scalp correlate
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This first 24 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for A normal awake and sleep pattern

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old right-handed woman for EEG monitoring with recurrent episodes of olfactory disturbance or bitter taste in her mouth, history of migraine, seizure medications on hold.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate and Keppra on hold
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG and seizure and spike detection software.  This was a technically acceptable 24-hour recording.
EVENTS: During the EEG monitoring session, the patient had 19 push button spells for a funny taste or smell.  These included 7:41, 8:04, 9:25, 9:33, 10:16, 10:30, 10:37, 11:11, 11:32, 11:44, 1:11, 3:05, 3:54, 6:59, 8:50, 10:09, 11:03, 3:05, and 7 p.m.  The EEG demonstrated a normal pattern with a heart rate of a 70-80 bpm.
INTERICTAL EEG:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient has somewhat disrupted sleep, but did get to sleep a little earlier on the night of the 17th.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS noted in stage 1 sleep.  Brief stage 2 sleep includes spindles and K complexes.
EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: NONE
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This 2nd day of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
Normal awake and a sleep record, although there was limited sleep.
Nineteen push button events without EEG change  on the final day of recording
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No evidence of epilepsy was found.  These findings were discussed with the patient and a diagnosis of nonepileptic seizures was reviewed with the patient, which she understood at the conclusion of her EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This 2nd day of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for Normal awake and a sleep record, although there was limited sleep. Nineteen push button events without EEG change  on the final day of recording

report:
History: 20 year old man with a recent head trauma with subsequent seizures.
Medications: none (unable to afford them)
Sedation:
EEG Type: Awake & asleep
Technique: International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40 uV, 10 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Fast alpha variant is frequent observed. Symmetric 5-15 uV, 18-25 Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent. Prominent POSTS are noted. During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present. No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair effort, and produces no effect. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) is performed while patient is asleep and does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep)
Alpha variant, fast
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy

During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves. During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.

Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving. Hyperventilation is performed for 240 s and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. HR is 70 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and asleep. No clinical or electrographic seizures are present The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 40-year-old woman with past history of stroke, migraine headaches, recurrent confusional spells, and evaluate for epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, gabapentin, Fioricet, Percocet, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG with most impedances below 5 kilo-ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Abundant stage II sleep is captured with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, POSTS, and beta spindles, which are harmonic of her typical 13-15 hertz spindle.  Hyperventilation elicited scant slowing of the record, but photic stimulation elicited a vigorous bilateral driving.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 40-minute EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a second normal EEG for this adult.  If this patient found to have frequent seizures, an ambulatory monitor or other tests may be helpful to characterize her spells.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 40-minute EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman with a 2 week history of episodes of paralysis.  She states that she can't talk or move.  Her eyes are open and she is aware of what is going on.  The spells last 10 minute.  Past history of asthma, dysthymia, DVT, cocaine addiction and diabetes.
MEDICATIONS:  Lasix, Flonase, Proventil, HydroDIURIL, insulin, Neurontin, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  This was a routine 20 minute outpatient EEG.  It is technically satisfactory, although there was a fair amount of muscle and movement artifact noted.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  In wakefulness, there is a fair amount of chew artifact.  Lambda was noted.
As the patient drifts off to sleep there is an increase in beta.  There is the appearance of posteriorly predominant slowing as well as electrocardiogram artifact and as the patient becomes drowsy there is a bit more head rocking, but a suggestion of slowing in the right occipital region relative to the left.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
HEART RATE 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is likely within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  There were no major abnormalities and the asymmetry noted in the occipital regions may represent head rocking artifact as the patient drifts off to sleep.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged sleep EEG may be of value.  In addition, if this patient is thought to have sleep paralysis, a formal sleep study may be helpful.  Alternatively, consider a 1 hour EEG in the lab with a muscle monitor to look for evidence of reduced muscle tone in states other REM sleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is likely within normal limits.

multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2, extensive
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:

very rapidly and is asleep throughout most of the recording - please correlate clinically with an
underlying sleep disorder.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 28-year-old male with childhood epilepsy seizure-free between ages 9 and 25, breakthrough seizure after alcohol ingestion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG, although impedance in the T1-T2 electrodes are just above 5 kilohms.  There are no previous EEGs available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Scant theta is noted in the background.  The patient is very drowsy with transitions in and out of stage 1 sleep with slow rolling eye movements.
In drowsiness, there are a handful of bursts of shifting slowing as well as a synchronous eye artifact.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in theta.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No sharp waves or spikes were noted in this record.  This patient demonstrates a great deal of eye artifact, but no definitive epileptiform features.  This seems to be a very drowsy individual.  To more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy, a followup study capturing more extensive sleep may be obtained.  The eye artifact described above is not a pathological finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal for an adult of this age.

report:
HISTORY:  A 19-year-old male with 2 seizures in the past month.  The patient reports that the seizures were associated with sleep deprivation before examinations.  Also, has a history of sleepwalking.  The patient is seizure-free since starting Keppra.  Positive family history of epilepsy.
INTRODUCTION:  One-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG capturing wakefulness and sleep.  Impedances were under 5 kilohms.  Hyperventilation was completed.  Both hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm with slow rolling eye movements followed by rhythmic central theta and then vertex waves.  Spindles were noted, but stage II sleep was not sustained.  The patient had frequent transitions in and out of sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  Hyperventilation produced a small amount of background slowing, followed by a drowsy pattern.
Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If additional clinical information is needed, a followup study or a more prolonged sleep study may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old woman with simple partial seizures characterized by a twitch in the right eye, with pain.  The spells occur 4-5 times per day up to 10 at night and may last 1 minute in duration.
MEDICATIONS:   Keppra and Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:   Routine, 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed   This is a technically satisfactory record.
The patient began to have a seizure with facial twitching without aura at the start of the EEG
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm reaching amplitudes of 60 microvolts.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  Very brief sleep with vertex waves, spindle, and POSTS was noted. but stage 2 sleep was not sustained.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for muscle artifact, but no significant driving.

Hyperventilation produced bilateral slowing a bit more prominent in the posterior regions. Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is remarkable for
1.  77 second burst of ocular twitching with 6 hertz muscle twitch artifact, otherwise normal background.

IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is remarkable for
1.  77 second burst of ocular twitching with 6 hertz muscle twitch artifact, otherwise normal background.

Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in beta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old woman, survivor of abuse with recurrent episodes of eye flutter, tremulousness, dropping to the floor with shaking.  Spells last minutes to hours and are associated with prolonged postictal awareness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  A 36-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  The patient had 2 events during hyperventilation lasting approximately 1.3 and 6 minutes in duration.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 11 Hz alpha rhythm, a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity, alpha squeak, as well as lambda.  Brief drowsiness was achieved at the end of the record and was characterized by attenuation of the alpha and an increase in beta.
Photic stimulation did not produce pathological findings, but did produce a driving response.
Hyperventilation:  Hyperventilation produced 2 spells of unresponsiveness.  The patient demonstrated eye fluttering, unresponsiveness, impaired ability to recall a code word and jerking of the upper extremities and shaking.  Her companion was with her and reported that these were typical of the patient's spells and, if the patient was standing, the patient would have dropped to the floor.
The patient was examined during the spells.  Although she was unable to recall code word, she demonstrated soft protective movements.  A normal alpha rhythm was noted when she stopped fluttering in her eyes.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This outpatient EEG demonstrated 2 behavioral events with typical clinical characteristics of a nonepileptic seizure and with a normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are typical of those seen in nonepileptic seizures.  The patient's primary neurologist was contacted immediately, and the patient was counseled today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This outpatient EEG demonstrated 2 behavioral events with typical clinical characteristics of a nonepileptic seizure and with a normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 35-year-old male with schizophrenia and epilepsy, learning disability.  The past EEGs with left frontocentral sharp transients.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, benztropine, hydroxyzine, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This adult had difficulty cooperating with testing.  Impedances were challenging and muscle artifact was difficult to eliminate.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a well organized pattern with generous beta.  An 11 Hz alpha rhythm was noted with generous, low voltage, frontal central beta.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, a 5.6 hertz rhythmic, mid temporal theta was noted.  This may be identified unilaterally or bilaterally with most burst of 5-7 seconds in duration, some somewhat longer.
No slowing was noted following these bursts of 5.6 second activity.  The technologist was not able to test the patient during the bursts.  Afterwards, no impairment of awareness was noted.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta with attenuation of the alpha rhythm, but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta and may accentuate the 5.6 hertz activity.  Despite the muscle artifact, photic driving response was noted.
Heart rate 66 to 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This theta described above as the characteristics of a normal variant.  This EEG was remarkable for a significant amount of muscle artifact as well as the failure to perform testing during the discharges.  A follow-up study will be obtained to more completely evaluate this patient's cerebral pattern.

Description:

symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old woman with history of posttraumatic epilepsy for 2 years, in her 30s.  Patient reported seizures with left-sided numbness and generalized tonic-clonic: involuntary movements with starring and poor responsiveness.  Past history of gastric bypass.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Lamictal, Actos, and Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION:  This is a 26-minute routine, digital video EEG with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was a technically acceptable record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was an 11 Hz, 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Abundant sleep was characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 30-year-old woman with history of seizures since age 17, 3 per month, treated with multiple medications.  Anxiety and substance abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, topiramate, and Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This recording session was terminated early when the patient insisted on smoking in the room, unplugged the equipment and demanded to leave.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
Background:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS.  The patient was relatively drowsy.  Stage 2 sleep included spindles. Recording was discontinued at 4:51 PM by the patient.
Event: 12:10:49 PM  The patient was awake.  Her partner was in the room.  She had an episode of speech arrest with head turning away from the clinicians. EEG demonstrated an awake pattern. No epileptiform features were noted.  After the partner left, the patient was noted to cry and then drifted off to sleep by 12:37.
Seizures: none
Epileptiform Activity: none
Heart rate 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 6-hour EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th normal EEG for this adult.  No epileptiform features were noted.  At least 1 clinical event was captured, although it was not seizure with motor activity.  This individual is thought to have epilepsy, alternative management strategies may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 6-hour EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 69-year-old woman with a left carotid stenosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Twenty-minute digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.

Heart rate irregular at 66 bpm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 36-year-old man with a 12-year history of epilepsy, last seizure at 1-2 years ago, here for follow up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra 500 mg, HCTZ, thyroid
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  It is a routine 20-minute EEG with acceptable impedances, aside from the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient is very drowsy throughout the EEG, but in maximal wakefulness there is 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  As he becomes drowsy, there is prominent theta within the frontal regions.  The patient was feeling asleep during photic stimulation, which still elicited harmonic and super-harmonic photic driving.  At the close of photic stimulation, patient was transitioning into stage 2 sleep.  Heart rate is 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through sleep, very drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are noted.  If indicated, a follow up study with photic stimulation in wakefulness may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through sleep, very drowsy patient.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 36-year-old male with epilepsy, seizure-free for the last 1-2 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, thyroid medicine.
INTRODUCTION:  1 hour digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a technically satisfactory 1-hour EEG with most impedances less than 5 kilo-ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  In drowsiness, rhythmic temporal theta was noted.  Extended sleep was attempted.  The patient was noted to have snore artifact, and POSTs but sustained stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles was not achieved.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  This is the 2nd normal EEG for this patient who has been seizure-free for 1-2 years.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 19-year-old female with new onset seizures with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.  Seizures began with an aurao  ringing in the ears.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  A 22-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was, on the whole, a technically satisfactory record, although not all impedances were under 5 kilohms and there was some muscle artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Central mu activity was noted, but testing was not performed to confirm this.  Drowsiness was characterized by rhythmic theta.  In drowsiness, slightly asynchronous eye movement artifact was noted.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles were noted in stage 2 sleep.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting in and out of stage 2 sleep and did not activate the record.
Heart rate 50 to 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits, slightly asynchronous eye movement artifact.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study may be of use.  The bradycardia may be evaluated by other mechanisms.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits, slightly asynchronous eye movement artifact.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 21-year-old young man with history of questionable seizure during sleep and intermittent dizziness and left-sided numbness.  He was studied to rule out seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  A routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation, photic stimulation, and EKG monitoring.  In the awake resting background reveals a moderate amount of 20-30 microvolt amplitude, 9-11 Hz activity posteriorly, which attenuates with eye opening.  Low voltage frontocentral beta-activity was seen, which was bilaterally symmetric.  Moderate amount of muscle eye blink and prominent EKG artifact was seen.  The patient appeared drowsy during much of the record with attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and diminished beta activity along with increased low to medium amplitude frontocentral 4-6 Hz theta.  Positive occipital sharp transients of sleep were noted (POSTs) followed by progression to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, central sleep spindles, and occasional K-complexes.  Hyperventilation produced no significant activation of the record.  Photic stimulation produced symmetric occipital driving.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 62 per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG and normal EEG, exclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, more prolonged recording or ambulatory EEG may provide further diagnostic information.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG and normal EEG, exclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, more prolonged recording or ambulatory EEG may provide further diagnostic information
